<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meets With Milosevic </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1103175394 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1633 GMT 11 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1103175394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 11 Mar (TANJUG)--Serbian President 
Slobodan Milosevic today received Karolos Papoulias, minister of 
foreign affairs of friendly Greece and the current president of 
the EU Council of Ministers, and his associates. 
  During the course of their meeting, which passed in an 
atmosphere of mutual openness and understanding, they spoke 
about the current EU policy toward the peace process and the 
resolution of the crisis on the territory of former 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, and also about Serbia-Greece bilateral 
relations and cooperation, the Serbian president's office has 
announced. 
  It was concluded that a fair and permanent solution to the 
situation in former Bosnia-Herzegovina could be reached only if 
the peace option prevailed over the war option and if the 
international community displayed an unbiased attitude and 
readiness to treat equally the rights and interests of all the 
three warring sides in this area. 
  President Milosevic stressed that the European Union had a 
huge political obligation with regard to lifting the sanctions 
against the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, in light of the fact 
that the Serb side has accepted its peace plan, the integral 
part of which is the lifting of the embargo. The European Union 
ought to fulfill its part of the obligations from that plan, 
particularly because it is impossible to resolve the crisis in 
this area without equal treatment of all the sides by the 
international community. 
  It was also stressed that maintaining sanctions against our 
country encourages those forces that are trying to realize their 
goals by force. It is of vital interest for all the countries 
suffering damage caused by the application of the economic 
blockade against the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia to launch an 
initiative as soon as possible for the lifting of the embargo. 
This is in the interest of the normalization of economic trends 
and the overall stabilization of the political situation in the 
region, in which the European Union should play an active role. 
  It was stressed that bilateral relations between Serbia and 
Greece were developing well despite the imposed limitations, 
which confirms the firm friendship and shared interests of the 
Serbian and the Greek nations. 
  The talks were also attended by Federal Deputy Prime 
Minister 
Zeljko Simic. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

