<H3> <TI>   Prices Rise as Value of Dinar Falls </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1103193294 Belgrade BORBA in Serbo-Croatian 9 Mar 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU1103193294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade BORBA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by M. Brkic: "German Mark--1.5 Dinars"] </F>
  [Text] The Yugoslav dinar continued to lose its value 
yesterday. BORBA has learned from reliable dealers' circles 
that the value of one German mark was between 1.42 and 1.5 
dinars in gray hard-currency transactions between banks, and 
banks and companies. 
  The erosion of the national currency has already been going 
on for 10 days. According to the decision by Dragoslav 
Avramovic, the National Bank president, the National Bank tried 
to intervene on the money and securities market by selling 
state-owned securities the day before yesterday [7 March]. The 
central monetary authority thus tried to prevent the further 
growth of the commercial banks' liquidity since it established 
that the money surplus in bank accounts was enabling the banks 
to pay the difference between the real and the official exchange 
rate. 
  Although the response of the banks to buying state-owned 
securities was good, the devaluation of the dinar was not 
halted. It is considered that the national bank intervention has 
not borne fruit because the cause of devaluation was 
ill-defined. The appearance of the difference between the real 
and the official exchange rate is not a result of the high 
liquidity of banks, but of the mistrust that companies have in 
the program of monetary reconstruction and the economic recovery 
of the country. 
  Representatives of the Federal, Serbian, and Montenegrin 
Governments met with [Federal Prime Minister] Kontic the day 
before yesterday and decided to try to take all possible 
economic steps to stop the devaluation of the national currency. 
Mistrust in the economy is growing from day to day, however, 
which can be seen from the exchange rate of the dinar against 
German mark over the last 10 days. It has constantly been 
falling--from 1.10 to 1.50 dinars for a German mark. Some 
businessmen and banks are pessimistic and predict that the state 
and the national bank could apply an administrative measure. If 
this happens, the prognoses are not favorable. 
  The commodity markets have already responded to the gray 
zone 
in hard-currency transactions. People who went to the market 
during the weekend noticed that the prices of agricultural 
products had risen. Apart from agricultural products, the 
prices of some other products, such as cement, iron, and other 
construction materials as well as ferrous and nonferrous 
metallurgy products had risen by 30 to 40 percent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

