<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meciar Addresses Parliament Before Resignation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1103151694 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1400 GMT 11 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1103151694 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1400 GMT 11 Mar 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Slovak Prime Minister Vladimir Meciar delivered 
almost a two-hour speech in the Slovak parliament today. 
  In the first part of his speech, he spoke about the results 
achieved by his government. In the second part, he expressed 
his view on his conflict with the president, whose speech of 9 
March led the opposition to propose a vote of no-confidence in 
the government. 
  Vladimir Meciar emphasized that the president had no 
constitutional right to control the government and initiate its 
dismissal. Vladimir Meciar proposed that either the controversy 
should be forgotten or the president should resign. One minute 
after [the president resigns], Meciar would resign as well. 
  Meciar also said that, if no early parliamentary election 
were held by the end of June, a referendum would be carried out, 
as a result of which there might be 90 government deputies in a 
parliament with 150 seats. 
  The prime minister offered alternative solutions to the 
situation: the government staying in power till the early 
elections or an agreement between the political parties or 
forming a coalition with the Party of Democratic Left [SDL]. He 
said that if the Cabinet is dismissed and a new government 
formed, the Movement for a Democratic Slovakia [HZDS] would go 
into opposition and its ministers would not take part in the new 
government. 
  Vladimir Meciar warned against the interruption to 
continuity 
should he be dismissed and expressed the belief that, after the 
elections, he would return to government. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-8673 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu049_d_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-049 </AU>
