<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslim Official Seeks Punishment of Abdic </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1103203694 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1831 GMT 11 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1103203694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Banja Luka, March 11 (TANJUG)--Bosnian Moslem 
Foreign Minister Irfan Ljubijankic has sought energetic action 
against Fikret Abdic, leader of the Moslem autonomous province 
of western Bosnia. 
  Addressing a session of the Moslem government in Sarajevo, 
Ljubijankic rejected the idea of granting cantonal status to 
western Bosnia, Bosnian Serb military sources say. 
  Cantonal organization modelled after the one in the Swiss 
confederation is envisaged in a Croat-Moslem deal on forming a 
federation in Bosnia-Herzegovina which would subsequently enter 
into a confederation with neighbouring Croatia. The deal was 
signed in Washington on March 1 under strong U.S. pressure. 
  Radical Moslem leader Alija Izetbegovic, who has sent troops 
to western Bosnia to force it to abandon the idea of autonomy, 
accuses Abdic of breaking up Bosnia. 
  Ljubijankic urged Bosnian Croat officials to suspend all aid 
to Abdic and cut off land routes to western Bosnia, arguing that 
this would help win over Abdic's followers for the government in 
Sarajevo. 
  Abdic, who believes that the Bosnian crisis should be 
resolved in talks with the local Serbs and Croats, has 
repeatedly accused Izetbegovic of continuing the war in an 
attempt to create an Islamic state and of sacrificing his own 
people to achieve this goal. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

