<F P=100> ROMANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Officers `Tense' Over Tinca's Appointment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1403193294 Bucharest ROMANIA LIBERA in Romanian 12 Mar 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> AU1403193294 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMANIA LIBERA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Romanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Dorina Baesu report: "The Atmosphere in the Army Is Tense"] </F>
  [Text] Sources within the armed forces have told us that 
the atmosphere is currently very tense among the officers, and 
even among the lower ranks, owing to the appointment of the new 
[national defense] minister, Gheorghe Tinca. First, because for 
the first time a civilian -- who is not familiar with military 
issues -- is leading the armed forces, and second, because many 
of the members of the Army Intelligence Direction claim that 
Tinca used to work for the Securitate, more precisely for SIE 
[Foreign Intelligence Service]. During the reign of the 
deceased [former dictator Nicolae Ceausescu] it was known that 
the Army and the Securitate used to loath each other. The 
memory of those times still persists. Had it not been for the 
precedent of the CADA [Action Committee for the Democratization 
of the Army, an organization of young officers immediately after 
December 1989], when the attempt by certain officers to revolt 
against the army leadership was suppressed, many officers would 
now react more harshly, the sources said. 

</TEXT>

