<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serb Official Cautions Against Arrival of Turks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1403161494 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1458 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1403161494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Salonika, 14 Mar (TANJUG) -- Biljana Plavsic, deputy 
president of the Srpska republic, who is on a visit to Salonika, 
has said that the possible arrival of Turkish soldiers in Bosnia 
could lead to an escalation of war, the Macedonian News Agency 
[MPA] office in Salonika reports. 
  If Turkish soldiers were sent to Bosnia the Serb political 
leadership would not be able to control the reaction of the Serb 
people, Plavsic said, and added that the Serbs in Bosnia were 
not defending just their own thing but also the Orthodox faith 
and Byzantine civilization. 
  Evangelos Venizelos, representative of the Greek Government, 
reiterated the Greek Government's position that no Balkan 
country should be involved in the war in Bosnia, MPA says. 
  The agency recalls a statement by Greek Foreign Minister 
Karolos Papoulias that Greece would consider sending its own 
Blue Helmets to Bosnia if the UN secretary general accepted the 
participation of Turkish peacekeeping forces in the peacekeeping 
operation in Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

