<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UNPROFOR Accused of Attempted Smuggling </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1403221694 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 2056 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1403221694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 14 Mar (TANJUG) -- The general staff of 
the army of the Srpska republic says that UN Protection Forces 
[UNPROFOR] members and UN helicopter units today brazenly 
violated the UN humanitarian mission and, by openly siding with 
the Muslim side, threatened the confidence created in our 
cooperation so far, according to the general staff's information 
service. 
  In a routine check at Sokolac heliport, it was found that in 
addition to a Muslim delegation, UNPROFOR was attempting to 
transport a large number of packages containing electronic 
equipment, uncleared documents, and a huge quantity of foreign 
currency from Sarajevo to Gorazde. 
  When a control team of the army of the Srpska republic 
insisted on continuing a thorough search, a member of the Muslim 
delegation, Edib Bukvic, deputy prime minister in the former 
Bosnia-Herzegovina government, opposed it. He decided that the 
delegation should not continue its journey. The two UN 
helicopters then returned safely to Sarajevo. 
  The general staff communique says that UNPROFOR had asked 
for 
permission from the general staff for the Muslim delegation and 
the chairman of the Srpska republic commission for POW exchange 
to be flown by helicopter to Gorazde. It was explained that 
this was a humanitarian mission that was necessary for the 
speedier resolution of the POW problem. 
  The flight was not permitted at first for security reasons, 
and the UNPROFOR command was advised to recommend that the 
delegation travel by land. Permission was nevertheless granted 
after the UNPROFOR command had asked the president of the Srpska 
republic and after both the Muslim side and UNPROFOR had given 
firm guarantees about the safety of the flight over the 
separation lines. 
  The general staff says that it had been precisely set out 
that the helicopters could only transport members of the 
delegation with their personal belongings and lists of POW's. 
When the helicopters arrived in Sokolac the chairman of the 
state commission of the Srpska republic was not to be found in 
either helicopter. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

