<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Plane Lands at Tuzla Airport </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1403164894 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1403164894 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Enes Osmancevic from Tuzla] </F>
  [Text] The first plane landed at Tuzla airport today after 
almost two years of waiting. The wheels of the plane bearing UN 
insignia touched down on the runway of the Dubrave airport this 
morning, or, to be more precise, at 1145. The landing of the 
first plane at Tuzla airport passed without any incidents. 
General Michael Rose, commander of the UN Protection Forces 
[UNPROFOR] for Bosnia-Herzegovina, was in the plane, as were 
some of the staff who will take care of the delivery of 
humanitarian aid to this region in the future. 
  As we have found out from sources close to UNPROFOR, over 
the 
next few days some of the equipment necessary for navigation and 
fire prevention is expected to arrive at Tuzla airport. 
  In a way, the landing of the first plane bearing UN insignia 
marks the fact that Tuzla airport has started functioning. As 
for the official opening, that will depend on the political 
decisions made at the level of the United Nations. 

</TEXT>

