<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UNPROFOR Commander Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1403180094 Paris AFP in English 1739 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1403180094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tuzla, Bosnia-Herzegovina, March 14 (AFP) -- UN 
commander Lieutenant General Michael Rose made a brief stop 
Monday at the newly reopened Tuzla airport in northeast Bosnia, 
as it prepares to restart aid deliveries to the beseiged town. 
  The British general, head of the UN Protection Force 
(UNPROFOR) in Bosnia-Herzegovina, spent two hours at the base 
which was handed over to UN control last week by the 
mainly-Moslem Bosnian Army after being closed since May 1992, 
shortly after the outbreak of the war. Peacekeeping troops have 
been clearing the airport area of mines left by a succession of 
Yugoslav, Serb, and Bosnian forces. 
  Rose had been "pleased" by the advanced state of repairs on 
the runway, base commander Lieutenant-Colonel Hans Jorgen 
Nielsen told journalists Monday. Asked about the date of the 
first flight into Tuzla, Nielsen said it was a "question of 
days." "We have been ready (...) for four or five days. It 
will come when the politicians have taken a decision," he 
explained. 
  The first arrival will be an UNPROFOR flight bringing 
technical material to prepare an airlift of humanitarian aid for 
the people of northern Bosnia, who are surrounded by Bosnian 
Serb forces. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

