<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Koljevic Statement on Independent State Proposals </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1403210094 Belgrade RTB Television Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1830 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1403210094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade RTB Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Statement by Nikola Koljevic, vice president of the Srpska </F>
republic, to a group of unidentified correspondents after talks 
with Russian envoy Churkin in Belgrade on 14 March -- recorded] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] [Unidentified correspondent] 
Was there any talk about the division of Sarajevo? [words 
indistinct] 
  [Koljevic] There was no specific discussion about the 
division of Sarajevo. There were some ideas that everyone would 
have authority in his own Sarajevo, and it does not need to be 
called the Muslim Sarajevo or the Serbian Sarajevo. It is far 
more important for us that people enjoy their political rights 
on those territories that they control -- this refers to 
Sarajevo -- than what kind of a name this will bear temporarily. 
  [Correspondent] Were there any demands for new territorial 
concessions, as it is evident that the issue of demarcation...? 
  [Koljevic, interrupting] No, the demarcation issue will 
naturally be very difficult; however, the style of these 
mediators is different. They would not raise an issue that has 
not arrived on the agenda yet. Above all, they want to create a 
very solid basis in order to accomplish success and have the 
most difficult talks about demarcation come last, when it would 
no longer be possible to cross over into a different situation 
without an agreement. 
  [Correspondent] How do you comment on the latest U.S. 
proposals about the possibility of an independent state of 
Serbian Republic? 
  [Koljevic] I think that these are very interesting 
proposals, however, we must study their legal implications. 
  [Correspondent] Thanks! 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

