<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Autonomy Demands `Unnecessary' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1403204094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2028 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1403204094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Novi Sad, March 14 (TANJUG) -- Yugoslav Deputy 
Foreign Minister Radoslav Bulajic said that the Hungarian 
minority in Serbia's northern province of Vojvodina already has 
cultural autonomy so such demands by the National Party of 
Ethnic Hungarians in this Serbian province are unnecessary. In a 
statement to Radio Novi Sad, Bulajic specified that the 
Hungarian minority in Vojvodina had classes in its mother tongue 
from kindergarten to university, that it had radio and TV 
programmes in Hungarian as well as its own theatres, cultural, 
art and sports associations. Bulajic's statement was prompted by 
his meeting with Hungarian Foreign Minister Geza Jeszenszky in 
Novi Sad on Sunday. Jeszensky urged Yugoslav and Serbian 
authorities to meet the requests of the Democratic Community of 
Vojvodina Hungarians (DZVM) for a cultural autonomy. 
  Jeszenszky paid an unofficial visit to Vojvodina to attend 
the centennial commemorating the death of Hungarian 
revolutionary Kossuth Lajos which was organized by the DZVM. 
  Bulajic underscored that the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, 
more than any other neighbouring country, enabled all minorities 
to exercise their human rights, even beyond the standards and 
norms stipulated by international documents. Commenting on the 
conclusions of the U.N. Commission for Human Rights adopted at a 
recent session in Geneva on an alleged violation of human rights 
in the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, Bulajic stressed that the 
commission was presented with misinformations coming from the 
secessionist movement of ethnic Albanians in Serbia's southern 
province of Kosovo-Metohija. The Yugoslav diplomat said he was 
confident that such misinformations and accusations did not 
exist in Vojvodina, because human rights of national minorities 
were respected in the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia more than 
in any other neighbouring country and even beyond international 
standards. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

