<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin Assesses Meeting With Milosevic </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1403153294 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1403153294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic received 
Vitaliy Churkin, the Russian president's special envoy. After 
visiting London, Zagreb, Sarajevo, and Pale, the Russian 
diplomat arrived in Belgrade with a view to finding a 
comprehensive solution to the Bosnian conflict. Here is a 
report by Slobodan Jankovic: 
  [Begin Jankovic recording] The Milosevic-Churkin meting 
lasted one hour. In a brief statement to journalists 
afterwards, Yeltsin's special envoy assessed the talks as 
interesting. Opinions were exchanged on many aspects of the 
crisis on the territory of the former Yugoslavia. Anyway, these 
talks were not planned for making important decisions, Vitaliy 
Churkin said among other things and noted that other contacts 
were also necessary before he could speak about any progress. 
  President Milosevic's attitude was flexible as regards the 
Muslim-Croatian federation, Churkin said and added that he 
personally was encouraged by the fact that the agreement on the 
federation could lead to a final peace solution. Churkin did 
not want to give a specific answer to the question as to what 
proposals he had brought to Belgrade, defending this discretion 
with the simple explanation that deliberations were still 
involved that were part of a permanent process. He said that, 
already in the afternoon, he was again leaving for Zagreb to 
continue his mission there. In reply to a journalist's question 
as to what would happen if the Serbian side refused to join the 
federation, Vitaliy Churkin said that refusal was not what the 
Serbian side had in mind when contemplating this idea. He 
reiterated that it was the turn of the Bosnian Serbs' to decide 
what they would do. They need time to study the agreement 
carefully, Churkin said and stressed that he believed that 
everything would proceed in the direction of incorporating and 
not rejecting the idea on confederation. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

