<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Encouraged by `Flexible Attitude' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1403205194 Belgrade RTB Television Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1830 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1403205194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade RTB Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Statement by Vitaliy Churkin, special envoy of Russian </F>
President Yeltsin for former Yugoslavia, to Snezana Rodic in 
Belgrade on 14 March; all questions and answers in English with 
superimposed translation into Serbo-Croatian -- recorded] 
  [Text] [Rodic] How do you assess the talks with President 
Milosevic? 
  [Churkin] I believe that this was a very interesting 
conversation in which all the problems in the former Yugoslavia 
were thoroughly examined. This was not a meeting at which 
decisions would be taken. We need further contacts before we 
can report some progress. 
  What I have detected is that at least in this phase, when, 
as 
is my understanding, the Serbs are in the initial stage of 
examining the confederation concept and other elements connected 
to it, President Milosevic has a rather flexible attitude. I am 
particularly encouraged by this and convinced that this 
initiative and the Muslim-Croatian arrangement in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina could be incorporated in the search for an 
overall political solution to the problems. 
  [Rodic] Did you bring any new proposals? 
  [Churkin] I offered some thoughts and impressions after the 
talks that I have held in the last few days; however, this is 
part of a continuous process. I am travelling to Zagreb today. 
I believe that the attitude of President Milosevic toward these 
issues is very flexible and constructive and I am satisfied that 
he is also thinking about ways not to reject the new ideas but 
to examine all possibilities that will contribute toward the 
overall political solution, bearing in mind also the idea of 
confederation. 

</TEXT>

