<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Praised for Plan To Send More Troops </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1403210594 Paris AFP in English 2047 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1403210594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Skopje, March 14 (AFP) -- Macedonia [The Former 
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM] Monday welcomed plans 
by the United States to send additional U.S. troops to the 
former Yugoslav republic to allow Scandinavian troops to be 
redeployed in Bosnia-Herzegovina. Defence Minister Vlado 
Popovski said on national radio: "If the (United Nations) 
Security Council approves an increase in the number of American 
peacekeepers or a replacement of the Nordic battalion, Macedonia 
will respond positively to that decision." Stressing the 
Scandinavian troops had done a "highly professional" job, 
Popovski added that he believed their replacement by U.S. forces 
would send "a warning to possible aggressors" against Macedonia. 
The minister added: "The work of the Nordic battalion on the 
northern border (with Serbia) has already led to a decrease in 
tensions and ensured a degree of stability in the region." 
[passage omitted] 
  Denmark, Finland, Norway and Sweden have a total of 800 
troops in Macedonia. 

</TEXT>

