<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Cabinet Ministers To Be Named 16 Mar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1403221194 Bratislava STV 1 Television Network in Slovak 
2100 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1403221194 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava STV 1 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Representatives of the opposition parties that, 
in fact, represent the coalition already, together with Jozef 
Moravcik and Roman Kovac, returned from the talks with the 
president of the Republic shortly before 2200. He announced to 
the president the name of the candidate who is to form the new 
government. Our reporters have just returned from the 
parliament building. Hence, we can offer you the following 
interviews. 
  [Begin recording] [Unidentified official] The parties that 
formed the opposition so far, presented [the president] with the 
name of a new prime minister to be authorized to form the new 
Slovak government. This proposed prime minister, approved by 
the president as well, is Jozef Moravcik. 
  [Unidentified correspondent] Did the opposition parties 
propose candidates for ministerial posts as well? 
  [Official] This was not the topic of the talks. According to 
the information given by the hitherto opposition parties, the 
names for individual posts are more or less known [to the 
opposition parties]. However, this [list of names] will be 
fine-tuned. There is a chance that the names for individual 
ministerial posts will be announced by Wednesday [16 March]. 
[passage omitted] 
  [Unidentified official] The Party of the Democratic Left 
will 
propose seven names [for ministerial posts]. The Center Bloc, 
as I called it this afternoon--i.e., the Alliance of Democrats, 
the National Democratic Club, and another independent club, 
headed by Mr. Bajan--will also present seven names. The 
Christian Democratic Movement will present five names. 
  [Correspondent] How many deputy prime ministers will there 
be? 
  [Unidentified official] It is expected that there will be 
three deputy prime ministers. One deputy prime minister will be 
in charge of the economy. There will be another deputy prime 
minister for the so-called superstructure or ministries of the 
nonproductive sphere, and a deputy prime minister for 
legislative matters. [passage omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

