<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Fierce' Croatian Attacks on Serb Krajina </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1503150094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1353 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1503150094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, March 15 (TANJUG) -- The Serb Army 
headquarters in the republic of Serb Krajina said on Tuesday 
that the Croatian Army launched, on Monday, a fierce artillery 
attack on sector south of the republic of Serb Krajina, despite 
the ceasefire agreement. One Serb soldier was wounded and 
civilian buildings were considerably damaged in the attack. 
  The Krajina Serb Army headquarters specified that the 
Croatian attack, which lasted all day long, started in the wider 
Kozjan region, southwest of Korenica, which came under tank and 
artillery fire, spreading then to the entire region along the 
front line, west of Korenica and Vrhovine. 
  The headquarters statement said that Krajina Serb forces had 
responded to all attacks, and the Serb defence line remained 
stable. 
  According to the statement, the Croatian Army violated the 
ceasefire in the territory of the western Slavonija (sector 
west) on Monday, opening fire from small arms around the forest 
of Prasnik. The Croatian actions ceased when the Serb troops 
returned fire, the statement said. 
  A twice extended ceasefire between the Republic of Serb 
Krajina and Croatia has been in force since Christmas. It will 
be in force by March 31, when the U.N. Protection Force 
(UNPROFOR) mandate in Krajina expires. 
  The republic of Serb Krajina has been declared by the Serbs 
in their ethnic and historical territories in Croatia, in 
response to Croatia's violent secession from former Yugoslavia 
and the downgrading of Serb civil and national rights by 
Croatian authorities. 
  The republic of Serb Krajina was proclaimed a U.N. Protected 
Area in spring 1992 following the conflict between the Croatian 
Army with the Krajina Serbs and the former Yugoslav Peoples 
Army. The U.N. peacekeepers have been deployed there under the 
Vance peace plan. Croatia has launched three offensives on the 
Republic of Serb Krajina since then, trying to take control of 
it by force. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

