<H3> <TI>   Offers Names of New Government </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603131794 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1100 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1603131794 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1100 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Anna Samelova reports from the Primatial Palace] </F>
  [Text] [Passage indistinct] Shortly before 1130, Prime 
Minister Jozef Moravcik left the room where he had submitted to 
President Michal Kovac the proposed composition of the 
government. 
  I asked Moravcik how the president accepted the proposal. 
  [Begin recording] [Samelova] Did (?he) accept it en bloc or 
individually? 
  [Moravcik] He voiced agreement with all of the 
proposals--that is, he approved the composition of the 
government that had been submitted to him. 
  [Samelova] Can you tell us the names of the new government 
members? 
  [Moravcik] I ask you to wait until (?this afternoon). There 
will a swearing-in ceremony at Bratislava Castle at 1800. 
  [Samelova] Last night, after talks with your coalition, you 
said that as soon as the government was appointed you would have 
the first extraordinary session of the government on [word 
indistinct] material and the current privatization process at 
some ministeries. Will there be a government session today? 
  [Moravcik] We assume that the government will be in session 
today. [end recording] 
  The appointment of the new government and the festive 
swearing-in ceremony will take place at Bratislava Castle at 
1800 today. The names of the ministers will not be announced by 
President Michal Kovac before that time. This was announced to 
journalists by his spokesman, Anton Bodis. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

