<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   HZDS Ex-Deputies Ask Kovac To Resign </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1503163994 Bratislava REPUBLIKA in Slovak 14 Mar 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> AU1503163994 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava REPUBLIKA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by REPUBLIKA: "Movement for a Democratic Slovakia </F>
Deputies to the Former CSFR Federal Assembly: President Is 
Calling in Question the Will of Citizens"] 
  [Text] Spisska Nova Ves--Aware of our decisive measure of 
responsibility for the founding of the Slovak Republic, we, 
deputies to the former Federal Assembly for the Movement for a 
Democratic Slovakia [HZDS] elected in the 1992 elections, issue 
the following statement on the current situation in society: 
  Our young Slovak Republic has arrived at a fateful 
crossroads. This happened on the basis of a carefully thought 
out and systematic course of action by the president of the 
Slovak Republic, who, by his address in the National Council of 
the Slovak Republic, initiated the process of destabilizing the 
Slovak political scene and a parliamentary crisis, whose outcome 
is the negation of the results of free and democratic elections. 
By this unprecedented action, which is without parallel in the 
history of European parliamentarianism, he exceeded the 
framework of his constitutional powers. As a result, the 
further development of our society is getting into the hands of 
political entities that did not vote for the Constitution and 
sovereignty and that were never favorably disposed toward the 
founding of an independent Slovak Republic. This development 
fills us with serious concern. We follow with the same concern 
the endeavor by the president of the Slovak Republic to call in 
question the will of citizens as expressed in their exercising 
the right of petition. 
  While we acknowledge the undeniable contribution made by 
Michal Kovac, president of the Slovak Republic, to the founding 
of the Slovak Republic, we feel the moral obligation and 
justification, obtained by the law on the termination of the 
federation, to appeal to the president's conscience to consider 
whether his remaining in the post of president of the Slovak 
Republic is in conformity with the interests of the Slovak 
Republic. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

