<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Responds </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1603115894 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1100 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1603115894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Zoran Vaskovic from the Serbian Assembly] </F>
  [Text] The Serbian Assembly has continued the discussion 
on the government's program and composition as proposed by Prime 
Minister-designate Mirko Marjanovic yesterday. Zoran Vaskovic 
reports from the Assembly: 
  [Vaskovic] Eleven deputies took part in the discussion this 
morning. Their speeches, and the speeches by another 50 
deputies still to speak, indicate that the debate will be long 
and polemic. With one exception, all the speakers were deputies 
from the opposition parties. They expressed the objection that 
the proposed program is too general and that it does not stand a 
chance of being implemented. They also demanded further cuts in 
the budget. The deputies from the opposition parties stressed 
that the cabinet of Mirko Marjanovic is not a government of 
national unity, as he had tried to achieve. 
  The only member of the ruling party who spoke today was 
Zoran 
Andjelkovic. The essence of his speech was that the opposition 
has not achieved any results in the communes where they won. 
  Let us repeat: We are facing a long debate, after which the 
deputies will vote on the new government. In order to be 
elected, the government needs at least 126 votes. Aleksandra 
Jankovic is currently addressing the Assembly and some 50 more 
deputies are still to speak. That is all from the Serbian 
Assembly. 

</TEXT>

