<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin Visits Belgrade, Meets With Karadzic </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1603114294 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1100 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1603114294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vitaliy Churkin, special envoy of the Russian 
president, has suddenly arrived in Belgrade as part of the 
latest peace initiative of the United States and Russia to find 
a solution to the Bosnian conflict. Immediately on arrival, 
Churkin met Radovan Karadzic, president of the Srpska republic. 
It has been unofficially learned that Churkin will also be 
received by Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic. 
  According to the latest statements by Churkin, the three 
warring factions in Bosnia could met at a negotiating table as 
early as next week. This round of negotiations would be held 
outside the framework of the Geneva Conference and would be 
mediated by the United States and Russia. 

</TEXT>

