<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Discusses Territorial Concessions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1503174994 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1738 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1503174994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, Mar 15 (TANJUG) -- Bosnian Serb leader 
Radovan Karadzic said on Tuesday that the Serbs were prepared to 
give up 16 percent of the territory they control in Bosnia. In a 
statement to REUTERS, Karadzic underscored that Serbs currently 
control 72 percent of the territory in Bosnia-Herzegovina. "We 
are ready to give up some Serb territory for peace but certainly 
not a big amount. I think that we will keep 56 to 57 percent of 
the territory." Karadzic said he expected the United States, 
which brokered the Croat-Moslem agreement of a federation, to 
guarantee that the alliance would not be anti-Serb. 
  American and Russian peace envoys underscored that the Serbs 
hold the key to a solution of the Bosnian conflict and Karadzic 
reiterated that Bosnian Serbs do not intend to boycott 
negotiations. "We will certainly join the talks," Karadzic said 
but did not specify when. "We do not reject talks about some 
loose association or some ties on the space of former Yugoslavia 
between former and newly-founded Yugoslav republics," Karadzic 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

