<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UNHCR Protests Serb Blockade of Aid Convoys </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1503145694 Paris AFP in English 1437 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1503145694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, March 15 (AFP) -- The office of the United 
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) denounced Tuesday 
[15 March] the Bosnian Serbs' continued refusal to allow 
humanitarian aid convoys from reaching the besieged Bosnian town 
of Maglaj. UNHCR spokesman Peter Kessler said his agency's 
repeated requests to the Serbs to allow humanitarian convoys 
into the north Bosnian town have so far fallen on deaf ears. No 
relief convoys have managed to get into the enclave, which 
shelters about 100,000 people, since October 26, when two UNHCR 
Danish drivers were killed. Since then the UN has carried out 
food air-drops over the region, some of which have missed their 
target, Kessler said. 
  Radio Sarajevo reported Monday that Serb troops had fired 
upon a group of people trying to retrieve some of the food but 
the UN, which helicoptered 10 British liaison officers into the 
enclave Sunday, was unable to confirm the report. The radio also 
reported that the Serbs had shelled the town on Tuesday. 
  Meanwhile a UNHCR aid convoy was waiting in the central town 
of Zenica for the Serbs to give it the green light to head to 
Maglaj, some 80 kilometers north (50 miles). The convoy of about 
10 trucks is being escorted by British peacekeeping troops. 
  Kessler said although Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic 
has given his approval for the passage of the convoy, local Serb 
authorities say they have received no word from their superiors. 
  The Maglaj region has become one of the hottest spots in 
Bosnia in recent weeks as the Serbs intensified their 
stranglehold on the enclave, formerly linked to territory held 
by the mainly Moslem Bosnian army and Croat troops. Bosnian 
military leader Hasim Sedic said the situation in the region 
escalated last June when the Bosnian army and Croat defense 
forces (HVO) -- allies until then -- began fighting. The Croats 
subsequently formed an alliance with the Serbs in order to 
isolate the Moslems. 
  Sadic added that since the March 1 Moslem-Croat accord to 
form a federation, the HVO has adopted a "passive" attitude 
concerning the fighting in the Maglaj region. He said the Serbs 
have some 80,000 troops deployed around the enclave and have 
helicopters and heavy artillery at their disposal. This could 
not be independently confirmed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

