<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Silajdzic Discusses Russian Presence in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603100794 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 0700 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1603100794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In an interview for the Austrian TV station ORT2 
following yet another round of Vienna negotiations, Bosnian 
Prime Minister Dr. Haris Silajdzic said: I am glad that the 
Bosnian-Croatian talks took place in Vienna. The Austrian 
Government has invested a great deal of energy and effort to 
ensure that peace is reached. We genuinely hope for peace 
rather than war. We hope that human rights, mentioned in the 
draft constitution, will become reality: the right to life, to 
freedom, to free movement, to differing views. 
  Asked to comment on the deployment in Bosnia-Herzegovina of 
Russian troops as part of the UN contingent, Dr. Silajdzic said: 
I was in Moscow three days ago. I was open about my concern at 
the way the Russians have become involved. Several weeks ago 
Zhirinovskiy visited the aggressor's territories and made 
nationalistically charged speeches. Soon afterwards Russian 
troops arrived in Bosnia-Herzegovina. The Bosnian Government was 
not consulted. The Russian troops have been deployed at 
locations in Sarajevo as well. We fear that Sarajevo will be 
divided. We fear a new war there. We shall do our utmost to 
ensure that a new Berlin wall is not erected there. We are, 
nevertheless, concerned. 
  Asked how stable the foundations of the new Bosnian-Croatian 
trust are and if they could be undermined again in view of the 
fact that until recently the two people have been engaged in a 
bloody war, Silajdzic said: Everything is possible. The crucial 
point is that a stable cease-fire, especially in Sarajevo and 
Mostar, has come about as a direct result of the current rounds 
of negotiations. This gives us encouragement and strength to 
persevere. We hope for the best, Prime Minister Silajdzic said 
among other things. 

</TEXT>

