<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Interviewed on Government Program </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1503203494 Bratislava STV 1 Television Network in Slovak 
1830 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1503203494 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava STV 1 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Prime Minister-designate Jozef Moravcik by </F>
an unidentified correspondent; place and date not 
given--recorded] 
  [Excerpts] [Correspondent] [Passage omitted] The previous 
government decided that state secretaries would leave their 
posts. Are you going to fill these posts, or will the new 
ministers abolish the decision made by former ministers? 
  [Moravcik] This decision made by the government is very 
unusual and is very strange. I think that our people could and 
should assess this measure and form their own opinions on the 
matter. We have not decided yet to rectify this decision made 
by the government. We want to have proposals this week so that 
we can fill the posts of state secretaries and heads of offices. 
[passage omitted] 
  [Correspondent] From the citizens' point of view, the 
content 
of government activity will be the priority. What will be the 
priorities of the government? 
  [Moravcik] The government will have only a limited period 
for 
its activity. The basic trends of its activity are already 
clear to us. The order in which I am going to list them does 
not necessarily mean what priority they are given. 
  The new government will have to secure political 
stabilization and the calming down of the political scene. It 
will have to secure the normal operation of state administration 
and to stop the deterioration in some aspects of its activity. 
The government will have to focus on the economy because that 
is important for all other areas. I have said several times 
already that it is important to stop the negative trends that 
are becoming clearly visible in the economy, and to lay 
foundations for the new government to build on these foundations 
after elections. 
  [Correspondent] The tasks that you have listed indicate that 
they will include measures that will be not very attractive to 
voters. Hence, from the point of view of a voter, this 
government may become less interesting. How do you view your 
role? Is it really going to be only until the next elections? 
  [Moravcik] We believe that a realistic picture of Slovakia 
and especially of its economy should be presented. I think 
that, when a citizen gets such a true view of the reality, he or 
she will understand measures that are inevitable to secure a 
certain positive development of society after new elections. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

