<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cot Introduces Successor, Protests UN Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1503140594 Paris AFP in English 1346 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1503140594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Zagreb, March 15 (AFP) -- UN General Jean Cot, 
speaking to journalists Tuesday [15 March], called for the right 
for the military to use air strikes in Bosnia without going 
through current cumbersome administrative procedures. His 
comments came as Washington and Paris accused the United Nations 
of lacking the will to use air strikes, after Serb attacks on 
French UN troops over the weekend. 
  Cot, the outgoing commander of the UN Protection Force 
(UNPROFOR) in former Yugoslavia said he noted that authority to 
order "close air support" had passed from the Secretary General, 
Butrus Butrus-Ghali, to his special envoy in Zagreb Yasushi 
Akashi. "I am convinced it is necessary to go further, and in 
some clearly outlined, clearly defined cases authority should be 
given to the military, which is not irresponsible," the French 
general said at a press conference to introduce his successor 
General Bertrand de Lapresle. 
  Cot has long demanded the right to order airstrikes and his 
insistence largely prompted his dismissal by Butrus-Ghali in 
mid-January. De Lapresle, using more guarded language, agreed 
that "there are cases which justify a very rapid response, not 
to make war but to guarantee our most important right, that of 
legitimate self-defence." [passage omitted] 
  French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe assailed the United 
Nations on Monday for its slow response, saying, "One must act 
faster and be more determined." French Prime Minister Edouard 
Balladur, who visited Bihac on Sunday, strongly criticized "the 
often overly long delays, (and) the too heavy administrative and 
political procedures" preventing immediate retaliation when blue 
helmets come under fire. 

</TEXT>

