<F P=101> Bulgaria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhelev Stresses Nonintervention in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1603185594 Sofia BTA in English 1837 GMT 16 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1603185594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, March 16 (BTA) -- In connection with plans 
by Greece and Turkey to send peacekeepers to Bosnia, Bulgarian 
President Zhelyu Zhelev sent a message to UN Secretary General 
Butrus Butrus-Ghali, the President's Press Office said tonight. 
Zhelev reiterated Bulgaria's stance for non-intervention in the 
war in former Yugoslavia and its call on the other Balkan and 
neighbouring countries to refrain from such intervention. The 
Bulgarian position is motivated by the fact that the Balkan 
countries are burdened with their past and any military 
intervention in the former Yugoslavia on their part, even if 
prompted by the noblest of motives, would arouse old suspicions 
and hostility. According to the Bulgarian president, such a 
development would aggravate the situation in the Balkans and 
increase the danger of a new Balkan war. 

</TEXT>

