<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   CTK Profiles New Cabinet Members </TI></H3>
<H4>   Deputy Prime Minister Ivan Simko </H4>
<F P=102> AU1703060694 Prague CTK in English 1859 GMT 16 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1703060694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 16 (CTK) -- Ivan Simko, the present 
deputy chairman of the Christian Democratic Movement (KDH), was 
today appointed deputy chairman of the new Slovak Government in 
charge of legislative affairs. 
  Simko entered politics as a member of the KDH, which now 
again becomes a government party, and which he co-founded in 
early 1990. His post-November political activity was preceded by 
numerous activities under the communist regime (toppled in 
November 1989). During his studies in Bratislava, Simko, along 
with local Catholic circles, helped establish Christian-oriented 
communities of young people. 
  Ivan Simko, doctor of law, was born on January 1, 1955 in 
Bratislava. In the late 1970s he graduated from Bratislava's 
School of Economics. He was shortly employed in economic 
research, later worked in the Department of Bratislava's Chief 
Architect. In the mid-1980s he studied, without leaving his 
job, at the Law School of Bratislava Comenius University, from 
which he graduated in 1987. 
  In January 1990, he was invited by Jan Carnogursky, then 
deputy prime minister of the new Czechoslovak Government, to 
work in his secretariat, where he stayed until the first free 
elections in June 1990. He was elected a deputy to the House of 
the People of the then Federal Assembly. He headed the 
Parliamentary Defense and Security Committee, and was a member 
of the Assembly's Presidium. He held the deputy's post until the 
next elections in June 1992. In 1991 he was elected as 
Czechoslovakia's representative to the European Parliament. 
  A few months before the June 1992 elections, the KDH 
proposed 
Simko to the vacant post of Slovak justice minister. Between 
March and July 1993, he was deputy chairman of the Legislative 
Council of the Slovak parliament. 
  Since late 1992, when the Federal Assembly terminated its 
operation (in connection with the split of Czechoslovakia into 
two independent republics), Simko, a member of the KDH 
leadership, has been working for the KDH. At the 5th KDH 
congress in September 1992, he was elected a party's deputy 
chairman. 

</TEXT>

