<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   CTK Profiles New Cabinet Members </TI></H3>
<H4>   Defense Minister Pavol Kanis </H4>
<F P=102> AU1703083394 Prague CTK in English 1959 GMT 16 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1703083394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 16 (CTK) -- Pavol Kanis, a member of 
the Communist Party for many years and its leading 
representative since the November 1989 "velvet revolution," was 
today appointed defense minister in the new Slovak Government. 
  Kanis, doctor of philosophy, was born on August 27, 1948, in 
Prague. After leaving secondary school, he was employed as a 
worker in the Povazske Strojarne Engineering Company in central 
Slovakia. In 1972 he graduated from the Philosophical Faculty of 
Bratislava's Comenius University and worked as a scientist in 
the Bratislava- based Institute of Marxism and Leninism. 
  In the first half of 1990 he was a deputy to the House of 
the 
People of the then Federal Assembly. In June 1990-June 1992 
electoral term he was a deputy to the House of Nations of the 
Assembly and a member of the Assembly's Presidium. 
  He joined the Communist Party of Czechoslovakia (KSC) in 
1981. Shortly after the November 1989 revolution, which toppled 
the communist regime in the country, he became a member and 
later a secretary of the Executive Committee of the Communist 
Party of Slovakia (KSS). From November 1990 to August 1991, he 
headed the KSC Federal Council, and later, until November 1991, 
the Federal Council of the Communist Party of Bohemia and 
Moravia (KSCM) and the Democratic Left Party (SDL) -- the two 
successor parties to the KSC in the Czech Lands and Slovakia. 
  Since December 1991, Kanis has been SDL deputy chairman. In 
the June 1992 elections he was elected a SDL deputy to the 
Slovak Parliament. 

</TEXT>

