<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   CTK Profiles New Cabinet Members </TI></H3>
<H4>   Interior Minister Ladislav Pittner </H4>
<F P=102> AU1703083794 Prague CTK in English 2024 GMT 16 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1703083794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 16 (CTK) -- Ladislav Pittner, a 
Christian Democratic Party (KDH) member, was appointed Slovak 
interior minister today. He was named to the post for the 
second time -- he was interior minister from November 1990 to 
June 1992 when he replaced Anton Andras who had to leave due to 
disagreement with Premier Vladimir Meciar. 
  Pittner was born on May 18, 1934, in Malacky, west Slovakia. 
As a secondary school student he was imprisoned in 1950 and 
along with other students sentenced to several years in prison 
for "anti-state activity and espionage." After he was freed in 
1953 he was employed as a worker for 14 years in the Tatra-Regen 
factory in Bratislava. 
  In 1970 he graduated from Bratislava's School of Economics 
and in 1975 became a scientific worker. Up to 1990 he worked in 
the Economy and Construction Institute in Bratislava. In 
November 1989 he was elected chairman of a strike committee and 
shortly afterwards chairman of the Public Against Violence (VPN) 
organisation in the institute where he worked. Later he became 
a member of the Christian Democratic Movement (KDH). 
  From September 1990 till November 1990 he was deputy 
director 
of the department for the protection of the constitution and 
democracy in the Federal Interior Ministry. In April 1991 he 
was named a colonel. 
  In the 1992 elections Pittner was elected a Slovak 
parliament 
deputy for the KDH. At the 27th parliamentary session he 
proposed a confidence vote in Slovak Premier Vladimir Meciar's 
government. 

</TEXT>

