<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 16 (CTK) -- Professor Juraj Hrasko, 
member of the Slovak Academy of Sciences and an expert in 
agriculture, was today appointed environment minister of the new 
Slovak Government. He was proposed by the Democratic Left Party 
(SDL), of which he is a member. 
  Hrasko was born on May 14, 1931 in Tocnice, south Slovakia. 
He graduated from the High School of Agriculture in Kharkov, 
former USSR. From 1955 he worked as a scientist in 
Czechoslovakia's Central Institute of Agricultural Inspection 
and Testing, in 1960 he became head of the Pedology Laboratory 
of the Czechoslovak Academy of Agricultural Sciences. Since 
1968 he has directed the Bratislava-based Pedological Research 
Institute. 
  In 1980 he was appointed a member of the Slovak Academy of 
Sciences. Hrasko focuses on comprehensive research, 
classification and development of soils, and organizes training 
of experts. 
  In 1950 he joined the Communist Party of Czechoslovakia 
(KSC), now he is a member of the SDL, for which he was elected a 
deputy to the Slovak Parliament in the June 1992 elections. 

</TEXT>

