<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kovac, Ministers Comment on Cabinet, Goals </TI></H3>
<H4>   Kovac: Government Reflects Stability </H4>
<F P=102> AU1703084794 Prague CTK in English 2100 GMT 16 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1703084794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, March 16 (CTK) -- Slovak President 
Michal Kovac said tonight the new Slovak Government should prove 
that Slovakia was a consolidated, stable, and democratic country 
which creates conditions for cooperation with any solid 
political and trade partner. 
  Appointing the new government, Kovac called on the new 
cabinet members to carry on the processes of transformation 
which have already yielded positive results. But he supported 
"a search for matter-of-fact solutions where the steps taken by 
the previous government were politicized." 
  Kovac explained Vladimir Meciar's dismissal by disagreement 
with "the autocratic method (of work) of the prime minister and 
some government members." He rejected their tendency to 
concentrate power and defended democracy and morality in 
politics. At the same time he praised Meciar's contribution to 
the shaping of Slovak statehood. 
  Kovac said he considered the Hungarian parliamentary 
parties' 
support for the new government an "expression of loyalty towards 
the Slovak Republic." 
  One of the major tasks of Moravcik's government is lessening 
"the incomprehensible and dangerous hostility between various 
groups of citizens," Kovac said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

