<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kovac, Ministers Comment on Cabinet, Goals </TI></H3>
<H4>   Finance Minister: Expect `No Miracles' </H4>
<F P=102> AU1703083094 Prague CTK in English 2147 GMT 16 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1703083094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, March 16 (CTK) -- Slovakia's new 
Finance Minister Rudolf Filkus said on Wednesday [16 March] that 
stabilizing macroeconomic as well as microeconomic indicators 
was the chief task of the finance ministry. 
  Speaking to reporters shortly after being appointed to the 
post, Filkus said no miracles could be expected of the new 
government. 
  "Slovakia must reach a market economy as quickly as 
possible," he said and added "we must stop indulging in reveries 
about the existence of some third way (of economic development)". 
  Filkus said it would be necessary to de-politicize the 
privatization process which, he said, had become a tool for the 
political concentration of power. The law on large 
privatization ought therefore to be amended, he said. 
  Referring to the state budget deficit, Filkus said that 
budget revenues had considerable reserves in the form of unpaid 
taxes, duties and in the area of financial control. 
  Filkus said he expected soon "to visit all necessary 
ministers and friends in the Czech government". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

