<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kovac Attends First Meeting of New Government </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1703090494 Prague CTK in English 2302 GMT 16 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1703090494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, March 16 (CTK) -- The new Slovak 
Government of Premier Jozef Moravcik, at its first meeting 
today, dismissed Slovak Police Director Frantisek Krajca and 
appointed Stefan Lastovka new director, Moravcik told 
journalists after the meeting. 
  "It is essential for ensuring full functioning of the 
police," Moravcik said. Interior Minister Ladislav Pittner also 
justified the change of the police director by the stand police 
adopted during the "pro-Meciar" demonstration and the attacks on 
journalists. 
  Slovak President Michal Kovac attended the first cabinet 
meeting. 
  "...The government has emerged from dire necessity to 
overcome the authoritarian method of governing and to create 
conditions for respect and tolerance of citizens... The 
government will orient its activity towards a realistic 
transformation policy, for which a stable economy is a 
pre-condition. It will pay exceptional attention to citizens' 
living conditions and safety and it shares Kovac's appeal for 
political, civic and national reconciliation...," the new 
government said in a statement. 
  Privatization Minister Milan Janicina said that the "wild" 
privatization by Meciar's cabinet in its last days was discussed 
at the meeting. He said that either today or tomorrow at the 
latest "appropriate measures" will be taken but he did not 
elaborate. Privatization will also be discussed by the new 
government on Friday. 
  Moravcik said that filling the posts of the state 
secretaries 
in the individual ministries would be a subject for further 
coalition talks, adding that the opinion of ministers would be 
taken into consideration. 
  Vice-Premier Ivan Simko declined to give details about the 
government-prepared manifesto declaration which, according to 
the constitution, should be submitted to parliament within 30 
days. 

</TEXT>

