<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   HZDS Petition Drive for Referendum Fails </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1603195094 Prague CTK in English 1515 GMT 16 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1603195094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, March 16 (CTK) -- A referendum through 
which representatives of the Movement for a Democratic Slovakia 
(HZDS) wanted to solve the question of early elections, the 
validity of the mandates of the "disobedient" deputies and the 
"purity" of money used in privatization, will not take place. 
  The 350,000 signatures which, according to the Slovak 
Constitution, are needed for the president to call a referendum 
were not collected during a petition drive organized by the 
HZDS, journalists were told by head of the President's Office 
Jan Findra and Ladislav Orosz from the Office's legislative 
department. 
  During the petition drive, which started in the last week of 
February and lasted until March, 422,054 signatures on 21,000 
petition sheets were collected and submitted to the President's 
Office for checking. 
  A total of 695 sheets were found to be invalid during the 
checking, Findra said, adding that out of the 399,212 signatures 
on the remaining archs [as received] 38,000 signatures were 
illegible and over 36,000 people did not put their first name or 
shortened it. So only 324,321 signatures were recognized valid. 
And after checking addresses of the people who signed the 
petition a total of 232,957 valid signatures were left, which is 
not enough for a referendum to be called. 
  Orosz said that the reason why the petition drive failed was 
that it was the first time that a referendum had been organized 
in Slovakia, its organization was not of the appropriate 
standard and the pace of the collection of signatures was too 
quick. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

