<F P=100> ROMANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   PUNR Senator Briefs Media on U.S. Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1503161894 Bucharest Radio Romania Network in Romanian 
1400 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1503161894 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest Radio Romania Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Romanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A group of parliament members from the National 
Unity Party of Romania [PUNR] held a news conference in the 
Green Hall of the Senate today within the framework of which 
Adrian Motiu, vice president of the Senate Foreign Policy 
Commission, presented a few of his conclusions regarding the 
visit he recently paid to Washington. 
  Referring to the way Romania is known in Washington, the 
PUNR 
senator assessed that this knowledge is simplistic and distorted 
due to the lack of information for which the diplomatic mission 
representing us there is to be blamed as well. 
  Mr. Adrian Motiu specified that during his meetings at the 
State Department and U.S. Congress, he explained that the PUNR 
is far from the description of extremism and that the verbal 
attacks of certain leaders have nothing to do with the way of 
action and thinking of PUNR. 
  Referring to the Hungarian celebration linked to 13-15 
March, 
PUNR believes that they must take place within a legal 
framework, without harming the national dignity of Romanians, 
our correspondent Ana Ionescu informed us. 

</TEXT>

