<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Comments on Tasks of New Government </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1703144494 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1100 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1703144494 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1100 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] In the next few minutes, you 
are going to hear interviews that correspondents Anna Samelova 
and Ivan Samel have conducted with the newly appointed ministers 
of key ministries. First of all, however, here is President 
Michal Kovac's answer to the question of what he expects from 
the new government. 
  [Begin Kovac recording] The fact that this government was 
formed five days after a vote of no-confidence in the previous 
government was passed shows that Slovakia has capable 
politicians who have the will to cooperate in the interest of 
the state and in the national interests of the Slovak Republic. 
I expect that, during its term of office, this government will 
confirm and consolidate this and will also give citizens 
confidence that we are not such a wrangling nation as it might 
have seemed recently. 
  Second, it is necessary that this government prepare the 
ground to ensure a calm course for the new elections that will 
most probably take place this fall. The government has very 
important tasks in the areas of the economy and social and 
foreign policy. In the economic and social areas, especially, it 
has to take measures to stop a further decline in the economy 
and the rise in unemployment. Measures need to be taken as well 
to increase the feeling of security among citizens who worry 
about their health and property, and about their social 
prospects. There are other tasks, as well, but the most 
important ones are those I have just mentioned here. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

