<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meciar Defends Referendum </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1703123594 Bratislava PRAVDA in Slovak 15 Mar 94 pp 1, 3 </F>
<F P=103> AU1703123594 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava PRAVDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Unedited authentic account" of statements made by Vladimir </F>
Meciar at his last news conference as prime minister in 
Bratislava on 14 March: "Still in Government Office, but Already 
in Opposition"] 
  [Excerpt] Bratislava--[passage omitted] 
<H5>  About the Referendum </H5>
  The institution of the referendum exists precisely to make 
it 
possible to change even the constitutional system. The French 
Constitution did not make it possible for de Gaulle to be 
elected directly by the citizens, and he thus proposed, acting 
in contravention of the Constitution, that he be granted this 
right in a referendum. Otherwise, he would step down. He was 
accorded this right in a referendum and this [the direct 
election of the French president] is still valid. This means 
that a referendum can go beyond the constitutional framework and 
that even questions can be asked in it that are not quite in 
conformity with the Constitution. This is the case because a 
referendum is the most democratic form of expression. The 
conclusions of an all-popular vote are generally valid and 
respected everywhere, and, because this referendum [initiated by 
the HZDS] is the first ever in this state, it deserves support 
and not to make voters disgusted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-8888 </DOCNO>
