<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Thai Deputy Prime Minister on Trade, Banking </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1603180894 Prague HOSPODARSKE NOVINY in Czech 15 Mar 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> AU1603180894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague HOSPODARSKE NOVINY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Thai Deputy Prime Minister Suphachai </F>
Phanitchaphak by "pen" in Prague; date not given: "Thailand Is 
Interested in Direct Trade With the Czech Republic"] 
  [Text] "Although our mutual trade soared in recent years, 
I believe that the potential has not been exhausted," Thai 
Deputy Prime Minister Suphachai Phanitchaphak said in an 
interview for HOSPODARSKE NOVINY. In Prague, the Thai official 
discussed trade relations with Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus, 
Finance Minister Ivan Kocarnik, and other representatives. 
  "In the course of the talks, I have introduced some other 
commodities, like consumer goods, fruit, and several farm 
products. I also spoke about projects that might be of interest 
to Czech businessmen, that we invest in the development of the 
infrastructure--the railroads or road construction, for 
instance. We need chemicals. It would be expedient to found 
joint Czech-Thai ventures for the production and distribution of 
numerous items. I am thinking particularly of glass 
manufacturing, but also engineering and car-manufacturing 
projects." 
  In the interview, the Thai deputy prime minister emphasized 
that he considers the conditions in the Czech Republic suitable 
for opening branch offices of Thai commercial banks that would 
not only support the financing of mutual trade, but also trade 
with third countries. "I used my sojourn for informative talks 
with the Komercni Banka. We also want to trade with the other 
countries of Central and East Europe, including CIS. We know 
that the Czech Republic has substantial experience on these 
markets, including banking experience. Thus, it could play the 
role of a mediator for Thailand. And, vice versa, Thailand has 
good contacts with the developing economies of Vietnam--for 
instance, Cambodia, Laos, and China. So, it could become a good 
basis for your activities on these markets. I also can imagine 
a free trade zone." 
  Before his departure for Warsaw, Suphachai Phanitchaphak was 
also supposed to meet President Havel, who, however, fell ill 
with influenza. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-8894 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu052_c_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-052 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

