<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Belgrade Approves Extension of UN Mandate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1603175894 Paris AFP in English 1736 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1603175894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, March 16 (AFP) -- Belgrade has told the 
United Nations it approves of extending the UN Protection 
Force's (UNPROFOR) mandate in former Yugoslav republics 
bordering on Serbia and Montenegro, the daily POLITIKA said 
Wednesday. However, rump Yugoslavia, known formally as the 
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (FRY) and comprised of Serbia and 
Montenegro, envisages introducing visas for UNPROFOR members, 
the newspaper reported. The force's mandate, extended on October 
4, is due to expire March 31. "The FRY considers the UNPROFOR's 
presence in ex-Yugoslavia is necessary until a political 
agreement has been concluded on the existing problems," the 
paper quoted FRY Prime Minister Radoje Kontic as saying in a 
letter to UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali. Rump 
Yugoslavia "supports the Vance (peace) plan (in parts of Croatia 
under Serb secessionist control) and wants it to be strictly 
applied," Kontic added. However, he recalled that rump 
Yugoslavia was hesitant about the force being staffed by 
countries which dominated the region in the past, such as 
Austria, Turkey and Germany. 
  Meanwhile the government committee on cooperation with the 
UNPROFOR decided, at a session chaired by Kontic, to introduce 
visas for UN peacekeepers. The government was to confirm the 
move shortly and decide what date the visa requirement should 
start, the newspaper said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

