<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin, Martic, Karadzic on Belgrade Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1603213594 Belgrade RTB Television Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1830 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1603213594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade RTB Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Statements by Vitaliy Churkin, Russian special envoy for </F>
former Yugoslavia, Milan Martic, president of the republic of 
Serbian Krajina, and Radovan Karadzic, president of the Srpska 
republic, in Belgrade on 16 March; Churkin speaks in English 
with superimposed Serbo-Croatian translation -- recorded] 
  [Excerpts] [Churkin] On Russia's initiative, official 
delegations from Zagreb and Knin will meet in the Russian 
Embassy in Zagreb on Tuesday, 22 March, in order to agree on the 
cessation of military and other hostilities. Thank you very 
much. 
  [Unidentified correspondent] Does this mean that you want 
the Krajina to become a part of the Croatian state? 
  [Churkin] No, this only means that we want the hostilities 
to stop and we want the situation in this area to return to 
normal. We hope that such an agreement on the cessation of 
hostilities will contribute to an improvement and gradual 
normalization of Croatian-Serbian relations, because this is a 
very important element for the entire situation in the former 
Yugoslavia. [passage omitted] 
  [Churkin] This was a working meeting, one of many that we 
have had in the past year and a half. We discussed the 
prospects for a political solution of the situation in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina in light of the latest events, namely, the 
Muslim-Croatian concept of federation. I think that the bottom 
line we agreed on was that any kind of future political solution 
in Bosnia-Herzegovina must take into account the interests and 
sovereign rights of all three constituent peoples in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina -- the Muslims, Croats, and Serbs. We agreed 
that there are still paths to be explored in order to further 
the extremely difficult negotiating process. 
  [Karadzic] We are very satisfied with the fact that it is 
clear that the Serbian people have their sovereign rights to the 
same extent as the Croats and Muslims; we have, of course, 
stressed our need to have special relations with Serbia, 
Yugoslavia, that is, and we must look for a solution within this 
context, within the context of realizing our sovereign rights 
and (?particular) ties; for the time being we do not see a 
solution, but we do see the way to it. 

</TEXT>

