<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin: Karadzic Fulfilled Promise on Tuzla </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603162394 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1533 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1603162394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 16 Mar (TANJUG) -- Special Russian envoy 
Vitaliy Churkin today said in Belgrade, following his talks with 
Radovan Karadzic, president of the Serb republic of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, that he believed that Karadzic had fulfilled 
his promise given in Moscow to open Tuzla airport. 
  Churkin noted that Karadzic had given this promise under two 
conditions: the presence of Russian military observers, which 
-- in his words -- was possible to organize within 48 hours, and 
the presence of Serb liaison officers, which was an element in 
the initial UN document on opening Tuzla airport. 
  The Russian envoy stressed that the other side did not 
accept 
the presence of Serb liaison officers at this airport but he 
nevertheless said he hoped other participants would continue 
negotiations with the Muslim government on this issue since this 
was a very important humanitarian issue. 
  We also agreed that in seeking a political solution for 
Bosnia-Herzegovina one should take account of the interests and 
sovereign rights of all three constituent peoples, he stressed. 
We agreed that there were ways of stimulating the difficult 
negotiating process, the Russian special envoy added. 
  Karadzic said that today's meeting was one in a series of 
working meetings characterized by a high degree of understanding 
and that he was satisfied with the fact that it had been stated 
in clear terms that the Serbs should have the same sovereign 
rights as the Muslims and Croats in Bosnia. The Serb side is 
trying to adjust its interests to the situation as we are 
determined to contribute to a final solution, particularly 
peace, Karadzic said. He stressed that the Serbs in Bosnia have 
a need for special relations with Yugoslavia. We must seek 
solutions within this framework, Karadzic said in conclusion. 

</TEXT>

