<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   British SAS Troops Deployed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1703123694 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 1131 GMT 17 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1703123694 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Charles Miller, PRESS ASSOCIATION defence </F>
correspondent] 
  [Text] Patrol groups of elite SAS [Special Air Service] 
troops are believed to be operating inside the besieged Muslim 
enclave of Maglaj in northern Bosnia. 
  Their presence underscores the determination of United 
Nations commander Lieutenant General Sir Michael Rose to lift 
the nine-month siege. 
  Surrounded by Serb artillery and mortars, the 20,000 
inhabitants have been surviving on airdropped food in appalling 
conditions. The last convoy to reach Maglaj was in October. UN 
relief officials who visited the area in January reported 
"larders bare and children nothing more than skin and bones." 
  Lt. Gen. Rose, who has spent much of his Army career with 
the 
SAS, plans to open the enclave to aid convoys preferably with 
Serb consent but using a more muscular approach if necessary. 
  With most of Bosnia quiet under two cease-fires, the Serbs 
are being pressured by the international community -- including 
their traditional ally Russia -- to halt attacks on the town. 
  Lt. Gen. Rose dropped several teams of armed British 
soldiers 
into the Muslim enclave earlier this week to assess the 
situation. The Ministry of Defence in London maintained its 
usual "no comment" on special forces operations. 
  However, trained to operate in small self-sufficient patrol 
teams of as few as four men, the SAS are the ideal 
reconnaissance troops to feed back information on frontline 
positions, weapons and conditions in the area. They will report 
back directly to the headquarters of Lt. Gen. Rose, who 
undoubtedly made the request for their assistance. 
  Although the use of SAS-type units in a UN peacekeeping 
operation is unusual it is not unique. American Delta Force 
troops were sent to Somalia last year in an abortive attempt to 
capture the warlord Mohamed Farah Aidid. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

