<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hopes for Croat-Serb Accord </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603234894 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
2300 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1603234894 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Franjo Tudjman, president of the Republic of 
Croatia, received Russia's special envoy for former Yugoslavia, 
Vitaliy Churkin, this evening. After the talks the Russian 
diplomat told journalists that they discussed top-level 
negotiations between state representatives of the Republic of 
Croatia and representatives of the Serbs from the occupied parts 
of Croatia. A meeting has been scheduled for 22 March. It will 
take place at the Russian Embassy in Zagreb. Having mentioned 
that he had already discussed these negotiations with President 
Tudjman, Vitaliy Churkin told domestic and foreign journalists: 
  [Begin Churkin recording, in English with superimposed 
Serbo-Croatian translation] The first thing to be done is to 
sign a very strong document guaranteeing that there would be no 
further fighting in the [UN] protected areas and around them. 
In the past few days we worked very hard in order to arrange a 
meeting at which an agreement would be signed. This agreement 
had been studied earlier, but for political reasons it was never 
either completed or signed. I hope that the agreement will be 
signed at the Russian Embassy in Zagreb on 22 March, but I am 
certain that it will not be easy. I hope that the attitude of 
the two sides would not be to try to squeeze out some 
concessions at the last minute, but to try to show that each 
side is the one which is being more constructive and prepared to 
make greater concessions for the sake of peace. 
  I hope that the attitude will not be technical, i.e., that 
they will not discuss how far, for instance, a particular cannon 
would have to be moved from a particular tree, so that the 
agreement could be implemented. I hope that the state approach 
-- based on a very strong desire for peace -- will prevail. I 
am certain that this desire exists both among the Croats and 
among the Serbs. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

