<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Albania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Envoy to UN Urges Dispatch of Troops to Kosovo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1203163594 Tirana ATA in English 1307 GMT 12 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1203163594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tirana ATA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tirana, March 12 (ATA) -- The Albanian 
representative in the United Nations, Mr. Pellumb Kulla, in a 
letter sent on March 10 to the secretary general, Butrus 
Butrus-Ghali, and the head of the Security Council, French 
Ambassador Jean Bertrand Merime [name as received], called their 
attention to the recent increase in the Serbian pressure on 
Kosova as well as to the danger of a possible expansion of the 
conflict, which would have consequences for the whole region. 
  "I ask that the Security Council conduct an investigation of 
the situation in Kosova at the earliest possible time, and I 
repeat the appeals of the Albanian Government for a discussion 
as soon as possible of measures that might be taken in order to 
prevent further conflict in Kosova," writes Ambassador Kulla. 
  The Albanian ambassador asks for the immediate discussion of 
the sending of United Nations troops to Kosova in order to 
prevent the spread of the conflict from Bosnia-Herzegovina in 
Kosova and asks at the same time that his letter be circulated 
as an official document of the Security Council. 
  On the subject of ethnic cleansing against the Albanians in 
Kosova, the ambassador writes that "hundreds of Albanian homes 
have been raided and 3,400 Albanians have suffered from Serbian 
police violence, and most of them have been imprisoned. In many 
cases, the Serbian police have ordered Albanian families, under 
the threat of death, to leave their homes and emigrate from 
Kosova. 
  Mr. Kulla also condemns the political trials against 
Albanians, stressing that "defendants have been tortured, 
serious procedural errors have been committed, and sentences 
have been excessive." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

