<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Albania </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Discriminating' FYROM Education Law Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1703123794 Tirana ATA in English 1122 GMT 17 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1703123794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tirana ATA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tirana, March 17 (ATA) -- Parliament of Macedonia 
[The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM] would soon 
approve a draft law on secondary school, which is another 
discriminating aspect towards education in Albanian language in 
this republic. According to reports from Skopje, the law 
contains discriminating articles and restrains the Albanians 
from full access to education. One of the articles states that 
only translated text books will be used in those schools where 
classes are taught in Albanian. Most of the draft's articles 
run counter to statements by Macedonian authorities for equality 
among all the citizens in Macedonia. 
  Sources from Skopje say that Albanians will not have the 
right to prepare original text books with a content to be 
outlined by they themselves in case the draft law is approved as 
proposed. According to the draft law, one of the requirements 
for a professor to teach in these schools is that he should be a 
Macedonian citizen and should have a full command of the 
Macedonian standard language. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

