<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Cannot Prevent Zhirinovskiy Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1603203994 Prague HOSPODARSKE NOVINY in Czech 15 Mar 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> AU1603203994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague HOSPODARSKE NOVINY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report in the "Domestic News" column: The </F>
Ministry Knows About the Visit From the Press"] 
  [Text] Prague--The Ministry of Foreign Affairs does not 
believe that the eventual visit by Vladimir Zhirinovskiy to the 
Czech Republic, "if it is meant seriously," could favorably 
contribute to the development of Czech-Russian relations. This 
is said in the ministry statement that was provided yesterday by 
the director of its Press Department, Marek Skolil. He added 
that the Ministry only learned about Zhirinovskiy's intention to 
visit the Czech Republic from the press. According to earlier 
comments by the Legal and Consular Section of the Czech Foreign 
Ministry, Zhirinovskiy's visit cannot be prevented. He is a 
regularly elected deputy of the Russian State Duma, which gives 
him a legal right to the diplomatic passport of the Russian 
Federation. Not even the newly drafted visa-free travel 
agreement between the Czech Republic and the Russian Federation 
will change anything on the status of the holders of diplomatic 
passports. 
  According to the Prague Lawyer Firm of Tomas Hofmann, LL.B., 
Zhirinovskiy can come to the Czech Republic without an 
invitation. Should he violate any law here, however, he can be 
prosecuted like any other person who violates the legally 
protected interests of the Czech Republic. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

