<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pawlak, Thai Official Discuss Trade </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1603161194 Warsaw PAP in Polish 1440 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1603161194 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, 16 Mar--Wednesday is the second day of an 
official visit to our country by Suphachai Planitchapak, the 
deputy prime minister of Thailand. During a meeting with Prime 
Minister Waldemar Pawlak, the state of economic and trade 
relations between both countries was discussed, while 
possibilities for investing in Poland were the topic of a 
conversation with Sejm Speaker Jozef Oleksy. 
  It was agreed during the meeting with Pawlak that both 
countries' ministers responsible for commerce would prepare a 
list of goods for mutual trade. The establishment of mutual 
banking contacts was also considered important. 
  The balance of foreign trade was also discussed. The balance 
is unfavorable to Poland. In 1992, there was a negative balance 
of approximately $280 million. The deficit is due, among other 
things, to large imports of Thai consumer goods, mostly textile 
products (clothing and underwear), by private companies. 
  Thailand is ready to invest capital in Polish markets, Sejm 
Speaker Oleksy said after the meeting with Thailand's deputy 
prime minister. 
  On Thursday [17 March], on the third and last day of the 
visit, the Thai politician will be received by President Lech 
Walesa and will meet journalists. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

