<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Hungary </F>
<H3> <TI>   Boross Delivers Speech Marking National Day </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1503182894 Budapest MTI in English 1719 GMT 15 Mar 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1503182894 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 15 Mar (MTI) -- Thousands attended a 
commemoration on Tuesday in the National Museum gardens, a 
historic venue of the 1848-49 Hungarian revolution and freedom 
fight. Members of government and Parliament were present, plus 
Budapest diplomats. A speech by Prime Minister Peter Boross 
recalled turning points of Hungarian history from the conquest 
to the present. 
  He cited the historical importance of the 1848-49 revolution 
and freedom fight, the ideas of March 15, freedom, national 
independence, and social modernisation. 
  Boross said distorted, alien ideas ruled the Hungarian 
people 
after World War Two. "The message of the March flame was there 
on October 23, 1956, when people fought for indestructible 
Hungarian freedom and overthrew a distorted system of ideas." 
  "This is the fourth year that we have celebrated March 15 
freely, and the third year that there are no foreign soldiers in 
the country," the prime minister continued. Boross said the 
tough years of change and recent traumas all point in one 
direction, that of the March ideal: To survive, and to make the 
life of the nation better, more secure and free. 
  "We have not solved everything, there is unfinished 
business, 
unsolved problems, but we are on the way, as we are fulfilling 
the order to survive and to prosper. Let us promise not to 
struggle with our daily problems today or engage in politics, 
but to bow our heads to the great figures of the nation. The 
spirit of March should refresh our public life, should give 
faith and courage so that we can cover the road ahead of us," 
the prime minister said. 

</TEXT>

