<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Labor Minister Misses Talks With Solidarity </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1203001794 Warsaw PAP in English 2246 GMT 11 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD1203001794 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, March 11--A several dozen strong group of 
Solidarity trade union members left the Labour Ministry building 
on Friday at about 2100 hrs after waiting in vain 10 hours for 
Labour Minister Leszek Miller. Representatives of five 
Solidarity regions have come to Labour Ministry to fix the date 
for talks between the government and the Solidarity national 
commission. 
  According to the unionists their arrival to the Labour 
Ministry resulted from Thursday's televised speech of Minister 
Miller in which he invited Solidarity for talks. 
  In an adopted statement, the unionists said that the fact 
that Minister Miller failed to show up means that the 
"government's declaration concerning its readiness to dialogue 
with Solidarity is simply a sheer lie. That is why the 
government side is taking on responsibility for what would 
happen in the country," the statement reads. 
  When the unionists were about to leave, Solidarity leader 
Marian Krzaklewski appeared and said that the government's 
actual readiness to negotiate had been checked. 
  He added that the protest action headquarters is to meet in 
Katowice on March 13 to discuss possible changes to the protest 
action schedule for next week. He announced that the protest 
action can escalate if the government does not start talks with 
the union. 
  The unionists were received by Deputy Labour Minister 
Andrzej 
Baczkowski who said that the government does not see any 
justification for conducting separate talks only with 
Solidarity. He explained that Minister Miller invited Solidarity 
leader Marian Krzaklewski to talks on social guarantees and work 
within the tri- partite commission for socio-economic issues. 
  On Friday minister Miller was paying a visit to Slupsk where 
he met with representatives of local governments and the 
unemployed. 
  The unionists represented extracting, metallurgy, power and 
arms industries. 

</TEXT>

