<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Government Crisis </TI></H3>
<H4>   Commentary Sees Meciar as `Victim' </H4>
<F P=102> AU1203145494 Prague CTK in English 1330 GMT 12 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1203145494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, March 12 (CTK) -- Vladimir Meciar, the 
architect of Slovakia's independence and for three years the 
most popular Slovak politician, has become a victim of a 
"Czechoslovakist, communist and Hungarian conspiracy," the 
pro-government daily REPUBLIKA writes today, commenting on a 
no-confidence vote in Meciar's government passed by Slovak 
Parliament on Friday [11 March]. 
  Peoples' fears of "what is going to happen with us Slovaks" 
are justified, the author of the commentary and the paper's 
editor-in-chief Jan Smolec writes. Politicians who did not move 
a finger for the independent Slovakia seized power, he adds. 
  The daily outlines a pessimistic picture of Slovakia's 
future 
after the "dismissal" of the "beloved" premier. Peter Weiss, 
chairman of the opposition Democratic Left Party (SDL), "an heir 
of the communists from whom we have not heard one word of 
sincere declaration to the people will now influence the life of 
society," the paper says. It gives also the name of another 
"accomplice" in the conspiracy -- Chairman of the Christian 
Democratic Movement (KDH) Jan Carnogursky who "voted against 
Slovakia's independence." "While the Slovak Metropolitan 
Archbishop Jan Sokol was praying for independence a Christian 
politician voted against it," says REPUBLIKA, alluding to 
Carnogursky. 
  These people together with "extreme separatists" will likely 
to lead Slovakia back to "Czechoslovakist or other dangerous 
waters. But we will not surrender. The fight for Slovakia 
continues," Smolec concludes. 

</TEXT>

