<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Government Crisis </TI></H3>
<H4>   SME: Meciar `Paid the Price' </H4>
<F P=102> AU1203154694 Prague CTK in English 1506 GMT 12 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1203154694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, March 12 (CTK) -- The debility of fourty 
years of communist rule is deeper rooted among some Slovak 
high-ranking political officials and the public than one could 
imagine, the independent daily SME writes today commenting on 
the events of the last two days in the Slovak Parliament. 
  "Slovak Premier Vladimir Meciar made a three-day sensation 
of 
such an ordinary phenomenom as the recall of the government," 
the paper says, adding that Meciar "paid the price for 
identifying himself with Slovakia." 
  "A state cannot exist or fall with the fall of one man 
especially a person who uses deputies merely to push voting 
buttons in parliament," the paper says. 
  It the Movement for a Democratic Slovakia (HZDS) of which 
Meciar is chairman, refused to form a new government nothing 
will be left for President Michal Kovac than to charge the 
Democratic Left Party (SDL), the second strongest party in 
parliament, with forming a new government, the paper writes, 
contemplating possible future developments on the Slovak 
political scene. A change in the distribution of forces in 
parliament after a new government is established could lead also 
to the replacement of the parliament chairman. "It is 
unimaginable for the parliament chairman to be a member of the 
opposition and the HZDS wants to become opposition, the daily 
writes. 

</TEXT>

