<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Government Crisis </TI></H3>
<H4>   Speculation on New Cabinet </H4>
<F P=102> AU1503161594 Prague CTK in English 1535 GMT 15 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1503161594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, March 15 (CTK) -- In advance of Prime 
Minister Designate Jozef Moravcik's announcement of the 
composition of the new cabinet on Wednesday [16 March] 
speculation has been rife about who the potential candidates are. 
  One of the five candidates for the post of finance minister 
is Mikulas Dzurinda, the main economic expert of the Christian 
Democratic Movement (KDH), a source close to the Slovak Finance 
Ministry has told CTK. 
  Dzurinda is an unambiguous supporter of the market economy, 
and may meet with opposition from the left-wing parties. In 
1991-1992 he was economic deputy to the Slovak Minister of 
Transport and Communications. 
  Moravcik said on Monday that the post of foreign minister, 
another hotly contested seat, should be filled by a non-party 
"professional diplomat." CTK has learnt from a reliable source 
at the Foreign Ministry that most suitable in terms of 
experience and skills are the ambassadors Eduard Kukan (at the 
UN), Frantisek Lipka (Paris) and Jan Kubis (Geneva). Also 
"close to Moravcik," the source said, is director of the 
Administrative and Information Department of the Foreign 
Ministry Dusan Rozbora. 
  The parties negotiating the new cabinet agree Slovak foreign 
policy should be coalition and not party-directed, as it has 
been till now. Other possible contenders for the post are 
director of the foreign committee of the presidential office 
Pavel Demes, and former Czechoslovak ambassador to Vienna, Magda 
Vasaryova, now head of the Slovak Society for Foreign Policy. 

</TEXT>

