<H3> <TI>   Republican Chief Says Zhirinovskiy To Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1403154894 Prague CTK in English 1307 GMT 14 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1403154894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 14 (CTK) -- Vladimir Zhirinovskiy, 
the leader of Russia's Liberal Democratic Party, will definitely 
visit the Czech Republic this year, although the date and agenda 
of his visit have yet to be discussed, Jan Vlk, secretary of the 
Assembly for the Republic-Czechoslovak Republican Party 
(SPR-RSC), announced today. Vlk met with Zhirinovskiy in Warsaw 
over the weekend and said he found the Russian leader's views 
very reasonable. 
  The Republican Party, led by Chairman Miroslav Sladek, 
invited Zhirinovskiy to the Czech Republic earlier this year, 
just two days after Czech Premier Vaclav Klaus, following 
Zhirinovskiy's much publicized and controversial tour of several 
European countries, said he hoped the Russian would not come. 
  During the tour, Zhirinovskiy said the Czech Republic would 
lose Moravia and all that would be left was Prague and "a few 
breweries where the beer will turn bitter." In an interview for 
Czech Television, he predicted that in ten years young Czechs 
would be vilifying President Vaclav Havel and cleaning the boots 
of German army officers. 
  Vlk, Sladek, and Zhirinovskiy met in Warsaw to attend a 
congress of the Polish National Front, a small party with 
similar extremist views. Speaking at the congress, Vlk called 
for the creation of an international association of nationalist, 
conservative rightist parties. The Republicans also accepted an 
invitation to attend the Liberal Democrats' April 2-3 congress 
in Moscow. 
  Zhirinovskiy told the Polish party congress that Russia had 
no territorial claims and its armies would never head west, but 
at the same time he would not allow any Western armies to use 
Poland as a path to attack Russia. If he becomes president, he 
added, he would protect Russian interests by any means 
necessary, "including nuclear weapons." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-8963 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu051__a94012" </HT>


