<H3> <TI>   Party Leaders React </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1403205294 Prague CTK in English 1920 GMT 14 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1403205294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 14 (CTK) -- Czech President Vaclav 
Havel commented on the planned visit of the leader of Russia's 
Liberal Democratic Party, Vladimir Zhirinovskiy, as early as the 
beginning of February, Havel's spokesman Ladislav Spacek told 
CTK on Monday [14 March]. 
  Zhirinovskiy was invited to the Czech Republic at the 
beginning of February by the extreme right Assembly for the 
Republic-Czechoslovak Republican Party (SPR-RSC), which has 8 
out of the total of 200 parliamentary seats. 
  Havel said on February 6 that "Mr. Zhirinovskiy has a 
diplomatic passport, he can come here and then it will depend on 
him what he says here and whether or not our authorities find it 
suitable to possibly expel him." 
  Zhirinovskiy announced in Warsaw on Monday that he would 
arrive on Sunday, March 20, for a two-day visit to the Czech 
Republic. 
  The Czech Foreign Ministry said on Monday it did not think 
that Zhirinovskiy's possible visit could help promote 
Czech-Russian relations. Marek Skolil, the ministry's press 
department director, told CTK the ministry learnt about 
Zhirinovskiy's intention to visit the Czech Republic from the 
media. 
  The chairman of the government coalition Christian 
Democratic 
Party (KDS), Ivan Pilip, told CTK it would be better if 
Zhirinovskiy did not visit the Czech Republic. "Political 
extremism has radiated many times and most clearly from 
Zhirinovskiy's statements, and it would not be good not to 
counter it only because he does not have real executive 
political power at the moment," Pilip said. He added that this 
could change given the current situation in Russia. 
  Otakar Vychodil (Civic Democratic Party), a member of the 
parliamentary foreign committee, told CTK that he personally did 
not think that Zhirinovskiy's visit could influence the 
political situation in the Czech Republic. 
  Miloslav Vyborny (Christian Democratic Union-Czechoslovak 
People's Party, KDU-CSL), chairman of the parliamentary 
constitutional-legal committee, said he was not enthusiastic 
about Zhirinovskiy's forthcoming visit. "Nevertheless, I do not 
think that we could prevent the visit in any way." 
  The opposition Czech Social Democratic Party (CSSD) is ready 
to call on the public to stage demonstrations to express 
disagreement with Zhirinovskiy's visit, CSSD Deputy Chairman 
Pavel Novak told CTK. He said "it is not only up to the 
government, but to all democratic political parties to use all 
possibilities of expressing their disagreement with his 
[Zhirinovskiy's] fascist views," Novak added. 
  Jaroslav Ortman, chairman of the parliamentary deputies' 
group Left Bloc (LB), told CTK that the Republicans' invitation 
to Zhirinovskiy was an expression of contempt for both the Czech 
Republic and humanism in politics. 
  The Communist Party of Bohemia and Moravia (KSCM) does not 
agree with many of Zhirinovskiy's statements which it considers 
to be extremely nationalistic, the party's spokeswoman Vera 
Zezulkova told CTK. 
  But she added that it should not be forgotten that 
Zhirinovskiy's party "has to a certain degree narrowed the 
maneuvering scope of those political groups and the economic 
lobby hidden behind them which directly promoted foreign 
interests in Russia and which wanted to treat Russia as a mere 
colony." 
  "It will be decisive for the development of our relations to 
Zhirinovskiy... whether he will respect the principles of 
equality and full sovereignty of all states and nations," 
Zezulkova said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

