<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister To Try To Prevent Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1503162394 Prague CTK in English 1415 GMT 15 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1503162394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Holesov, south Moravia, March 15 (CTK) -- Czech 
Interior Minister Jan Ruml said today he would take all 
necessary steps to prevent Vladimir Zhirinovskiy, chairman of 
Russia's Liberal Democratic Party, from staying in the Czech 
Republic. 
  Zhirinovskiy is expected to arrive on March 20 for a two-day 
visit. He was invited by Miroslav Sladek's Assembly for the 
Republic-Republican Party of Czechoslovakia (SPR-RSC) earlier 
this year, two days after Czech Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus said 
he hoped the Russian leader would not come to the Czech Republic. 
  The Czech Republic has no visa requirement for Russian 
citizens, and as a member of Russia's parliament Zhirinovskiy 
may also avail himself of his diplomatic passport, so that no 
legal obstacles exist to prevent him from entering the country. 
  Nevertheless, Ruml said he would look into other 
possibilities. "In the law on foreigners' stays on Czech 
territory there is a passage I will make use of. It states that 
a visit can be denied for a year if, among other things, it is 
absolutely necessary for the state's security, the maintenance 
of public order, the protection of health, or the rights and 
freedoms of others. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

